There are multiple crop operations in the zcomp algorithm, including one crop per feature and fiducial. The current crop method iterates over the entire point cloud, which can contain 50+ million points. This is CPU-expensive and takes approximately 650 ms per crop, regardless of crop size. A more efficient approach is to build a spatial index for the point cloud once, then reuse that index for all subsequent crop operations. This allows each crop to inspect only the points located in the relevant spatial cells instead of scanning the full cloud every time, significantly reducing total processing time when many small crops are required.